\begin_layout Standard
Calculate the volume of the object trapped between the spheres
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{2}+y^{2}+z^{2}=4
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x^{2}+\left(y+2\right)^{2}+z^{2}=4
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
From those we get 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Meaning the intersection of the shells of the spheres is 
\begin_inset Formula $y=-1$
\end_inset

 ; 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{2}+z^{2}=3$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
So All we need it to calculate half of the intersection area and multiply
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 (the magic of symmetry).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let's look at the cut parallel to plane 
\begin_inset Formula $XZ$
\end_inset

 (from 
\begin_inset Formula $-2\leq y\leq-1$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The radius of the circle of the cut at 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{0}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{4-y_{0}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 so the area in the cut is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(4-y_{0}^{2}\right)\pi$
\end_inset

.
 So we can integrate over all the cuts:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{-2}^{-1}4\pi-\pi y^{2}dy=4\pi-\frac{\pi}{3}\left(\left(-1\right)^{3}-\left(-2\right)^{3}\right)=4\pi-\frac{\pi}{3}\left(-1+8\right)=\frac{5\pi}{3}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
And now we multiply but 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

 and get the entire area trapped
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
10\pi/3
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

