\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\forall\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

 given that 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 copies the cube 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[3,3+\varepsilon\right]\times\left[2,2+\varepsilon\right]\times\left[1,1+\varepsilon\right]$
\end_inset

 to an object with volume 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\varepsilon\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
RTP: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{\varepsilon\ra0}\frac{V\left(\varepsilon\right)}{\varepsilon^{3}}=L
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
The Jacobean is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
J=\frac{1}{\begin{matrix}2x & 2y & 0\\
1 & -1 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{matrix}}=\frac{1}{-2x-2y}=-\frac{1}{2\left(x+y\right)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|J^{-1}\left(3,2,1\right)\right|=\left|-2\left(3+2\right)\right|=\left|-10\right|=10$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
So 
\begin_inset Formula $V\left(\varepsilon\right)=10\cdot\varepsilon^{3}$
\end_inset

 (because we can take out 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|J^{-1}\right|$
\end_inset

 when we do a reverse variable interchange in the integral to calculate
 the volume in the new space).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
And thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{\varepsilon\ra0}\frac{V\left(\varepsilon\right)}{\varepsilon^{3}}=\lim_{\varepsilon\ra0}\frac{10\varepsilon^{3}}{\varepsilon^{3}}=\lim_{\varepsilon\ra0}10=10$
\end_inset

.
